{"title":"All new Ibis Exie is a super light & capable XC mountain bike that’s Made in the USA","link":"https://bikerumor.com/2021/06/30/all-new-ibis-exie-is-a-super-light-capable-xc-mountain-bike-thats-made-in-the-usa/","date":1625100521000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><div><p>Ibis claims that when they started their Carbon 831 Lab, they didn’t initially set out with the goal of in-house manufacturing. Initially, they simply wanted to use it as a tool for prototyping and development, but along the way, they got curious. What&nbsp;<em>is</em> possible when it comes to making carbon frames in the USA? What would Ibis have to do to make it feasible?</p><p>They set out to find that answer with a trial run of a single size for a single model. <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/2018/08/08/ibis-cycles-starts-usa-production-w-small-ripley-ls-from-carbon-831/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Those Small Ripleys</a> were a success, and it led Ibis to pursue their first model completely built in-house – the all new Ibis Exie.</p><p><span><iframe width=\"696\" height=\"392\" data-ezsrc=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/JAJXv-h_afA?version=3&amp;rel=1&amp;showsearch=0&amp;showinfo=1&amp;iv_load_policy=1&amp;fs=1&amp;hl=en-US&amp;autohide=2&amp;start=1&amp;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation\" ezoid=\"0.600157452812897\"></iframe></span></p><p>Now Ibis kind of snuck this bike onto their site without much information, but we have a general idea of what’s coming thanks to the video above. In it, Ibis partner and CEO Hans Heim details the process that got them here, along with additional commentary by their Development Engineer Preston Sandusky and Engineering Manager Colin Hughe.</p><p>Remaining true to their claims with the initial Carbon 831 project, Ibis says two main things really set their process apart from Asian carbon factories like those that make other Ibis models in Taiwan and Vietnam: the layup and the molds.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3.jpg\" alt=\"Ibis Exie carbon plies\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3.jpg 1200w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-297x198.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-800x533.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-120x80.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-768x512.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-696x464.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-1068x712.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-630x420.jpg 630w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb20 src ng ngcb20 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3.jpg 1200w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-297x198.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-800x533.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-120x80.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-768x512.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-696x464.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-1068x712.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201630/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-3-630x420.jpg 630w\"></a></p><p>While other factories certainly have automated cutters, Ibis claims that they use them differently. Instead of making many smaller pieces that require a lot of time to lay by hand, Ibis makes fewer, more complicated and intricate pieces that reduce the parts count from 300-400 pieces, down to about 100-120. That saves time both prepping the materials and in the layup process, which helps cut the overall time needed to make a frame substantially (the claim is roughly 40%).</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201635/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-9.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/30201635/Ibis-Exie-Pajaro-Manufacturing-9.jpg\" alt=\"Ibis Exie frame being placed into a mold\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" data-e